To access Acumatica ERP, users must pass authentication to confirm their identity (see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP]). Then users pass authorization to determine their access rights to the system objects, such as forms. Users can access only the objects they are allowed to use and perform only the actions they are authorized to based on their access rights. In Acumatica ERP, a system object to which access rights can be set up can be a particular form, container of form elements, form element, or wiki.{br}
If Acumatica ERP is integrated with Microsoft Active Directory, Microsoft Active Directory Federation Services, or Microsoft Azure Active Directory, the user&rsquo;s roles may be automatically assigned, based on Active Directory groups. For details, see [HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_Integration_with_Active_Directory|Integration with Active Directory], [HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_ADFS_Integration|Integration with AD FS], and [HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_AzureAD_Integration|Integration with Azure Active Directory].{br}
In this topic, user access rights in Acumatica ERP are described.{br}{TOC} ==Configuration of User Access Rights== You need to perform the following steps to set up access rights to system objects for users in Acumatica ERP:[anchor|#_8b055470-b62c-46d2-ae34-f51b84c6653f] #You create user roles on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form according to the responsibilities of your organization' employees who will work with Acumatica ERP. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access]. #You set up access rights for user roles to Acumatica ERP objects, depending on the tasks performed by users with these user roles. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role_Configuration|Access Rights for Roles]. #You assign user roles with user accounts to provide users of your Acumatica ERP instance with access rights to system objects. You can do this in two ways: #*To assign multiple users a selected role, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form. For example, you use this way when you have created a new role and want to assign it to existing users. #*To assign multiple roles to a selected user, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_10|Users] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201010|SM201010]) form. For example, you use this way when you have created a new user account and want to assign it existing roles. User account configuration is described in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP]. #Optional: You use user types to simplify the assignment of user roles to users. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts#_775858a7-972a-4226-ac5d-7e74ae894419|User Types]. #Optional: You delegate to external users the rights to create users—for instance, you might delegate these rights to external administrators of Self-Service Portal, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Delegation_User_Creation_Rights|To Delegate the Right to Create Users]. '''Ability to Track Access Rights''' You can track access rights to different objects by using the following forms:[anchor|#_f373dd60-7577-4fa3-ba3c-062d038e415d] *[HelpRoot_ReportReference\SM_65_17_00|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM651700|SM651700]): Gives you the ability to build a report to view access rights by each screen (that is, form). *[HelpRoot_ReportReference\SM_65_15_00|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM651500|SM651500]): Gives you the ability to view access rights by each user role. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_55|Access Rights by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201055|SM201055]): Gives you the ability to view the computed access rights of each user to every system object.
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role_Configuration|Access Rights for Roles] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_Integration_with_Active_Directory|Integration with Active Directory] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_ADFS_Integration|Integration with AD FS] *[HelpRoot_Integration\US__con_AzureAD_Integration|Integration with Azure Active Directory] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Delegation_User_Creation_Rights|To Delegate the Right to Create Users] *[HelpRoot_ReportReference\SM_65_15_00|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM651500|SM651500]) *[HelpRoot_ReportReference\SM_65_17_00|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM651700|SM651700]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_55|Access Rights by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201055|SM201055]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_10|Users] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201010|SM201010])

Acumatica ERP uses roles to restrict access to the system. You assign users one role or multiple roles, and based on these assignments, the users are then granted the appropriate levels of access to system objects. You never assign access rights to individual users. With this approach, you can quickly and easily control access to system objects because changing the access rights of a role affects all the users with the role assigned. A user with no role assigned has no access to system objects.{br}{TOC} ==Roles== Users who work with Acumatica ERP have specific job responsibilities that define their access level to forms, records, and operations on the records. User roles in Acumatica ERP are sets of access rights designed for convenient management of access rights for users with similar responsibilities in the system.{br}
On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form, you create a role and assign it to as many user accounts as needed. If you need to change access rights for all users assigned to a role, you change the settings of the role instead of editing each user's permissions. When new users are hired in your organization, you assign a role to a new user. When existing users change their position in the company, you simply change set of roles according to their new responsibilities. {br}
We recommend that you configure the roles so that a user with a role has only the access rights necessary to perform typical tasks. It is better to give a user multiple roles than to create complicated roles that overlap with existing ones. For example, suppose that the ''Accounting Manager'' role has broader access rights than the ''Accountant'' role. Instead of giving the ''Account Manager'' role the same privileges the ''Accountant'' role has, give a user in a managerial position the ''Accountant'' role along with the ''Accounting Manager'' role. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role_Configuration|Access Rights for Roles].((({S:Hint}The process of defining task-based roles requires in-depth knowledge of both the organization&rsquo;s business processes and the Acumatica ERP approach to security. ))) ==Built-In Roles== For ease of defining and administering roles, Acumatica ERP provides a set of built-in roles that are stored in the System company (for details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Support_of_Multiple_Companies|Support of Multiple Tenants]). Built-in roles are always supplied with the system and cannot be deleted. {br}
Some of these roles grant the users access to special functionality, and some of the roles are used by the system and should not be assigned to users manually.{br}
The following built-in roles are available in the system:[anchor|#ul_bgy_lrm_gk] *''Administrator'': A user with this role has full access to all system objects, and any access restrictions to system objects are not applied to this role. Therefore we recommend that you assign users to this role only during initial system setup so they can define roles and enter users. Then assign the role only in extraordinary cases. We recommend that you create a user role for system administrators with access only to Acumatica ERP forms that are used for configuration and management of the system. *:((({S:Warn}A user with this role cannot publish reports and modify original dashboards (which have an owner role other than ''Administrator''). ))) *''Anonymous'': This role is reserved for system use. *''AP Clerk'': A user with this role has access to accounts payable functions, as well as read-only access to accounts payable settings and general ledger transactions. *''AP Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related to accounts payable as well as read-only access to general ledger transactions. *''AP Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to accounts payable functions. *''AR Clerk'': A user with this role has access to accounts receivable functions as well as read-only access to accounts receivable settings and general ledger transactions. *''AR Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related to accounts receivable as well as read-only access to general ledger transactions. *''AR Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to accounts receivable functions. *''BI'': A user with this role can access the ''BI Views''—that is, the preconfigured generic inquiries that are exposed through the OData protocol, such as ''BI-Opportunities''. For more information, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\CU__con_OData|OData Support]. *''BusinessDateOverride'': A user with this role can change the business date in the info area of Acumatica ERP. This role appears only if the ''Secure Business Date'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. For details, see [HelpRoot_GettingStarted\Setting_Business_Date|To Change the Business Date]. *''CA Clerk'': A user with this role has access to cash management functions and read-only access to cash management settings. *''CA Admin'': A user with this role has access to cash management functions and settings. *''CA Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to cash management functions. *''CM Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related to currency management. *''CM Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to currency management functions. *''CS Admin'': Users with this role can access system functions and configuration entities that might be needed by users in financial positions. More specifically, they have administrative permissions to configure most of the common settings, including segmented keys, numbering sequences, tasks, and business process scenarios, as well as to manage business events, notification templates, and document templates. Users with the ''CS Admin'' role also have full access to row-level security settings and most of the integration functions. *''Customizer'': A user with this role can customize Acumatica ERP applications. For details, see [HelpRoot_Dev_Customization\CG_GL_Stages_Role|To Assign the Customizer Role to a User Account]. *''DashboardDesigner'': The system automatically designates this role as a dashboard owner role for dashboards that were created in previous versions of Acumatica ERP. We recommend that you create specific roles for users who should own particular dashboards. For details, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\CU__con_Dashboards|Dashboard Pages]. *''Data Privacy Controller'': A user with this role has access to the compliance tools for General Data Protection Regulation. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\GD__MNG_Handling_Personal_Data|Handling Personal Data]. *''DR Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related to deferred revenue. *''DR Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to deferred revenue functions. *''FA Clerk'': A user with this role has access to fixed asset functions, as well as read-only access to fixed asset settings. *''FA Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related to fixed assets. *''FA Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to fixed asset functions. *''Field-Level Audit'': A user with this role can view the audit trail directly from an audited form. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Managing_Field_Level_Audit_Access|Management of Access to Field-Level Audit Functionality]. *''Financial Supervisor'': A user with this role can post to closed financial periods, while all other users are not able to work with these periods (when the '''Restrict Access to Closed Periods''' check box is selected on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\GL_10_20_00|General Ledger Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=GL102000|GL102000]) form). A financial supervisor can also reopen ''Closed'' periods and unlock ''Locked'' periods. *''GL Clerk'': A user with this role has access to general ledger functions, as well as read-only access to general ledger settings. *''GL Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related with the general ledger. *''GL Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to general ledger functions. *''Guest'': This role is used for backward compatibility. *''Internal Employee'': Users with this role have full access to personal settings, tasks, events, email, and time cards, as well as expense receipts and claims. Additionally, these users can view Help. *''Internal User'': A user with this role can change personal settings, and view Help. It is automatically assigned to all user accounts linked with the ''Employee'' user type. *''Portal Admin'': A user with this role can access the Acumatica Self-Service Portal configuration forms and configure Self-Service Portal. For more information about Acumatica Self-Service Portal, see [HelpRoot_SS_Portal_Admin\SP_SP_00_00| Self-Service Portal]. *''Portal User'': A user with this role can access Self-Service Portal. You should assign this role only to contacts who must have access to Self-Service Portal. For more information about Acumatica Self-Service Portal, see [HelpRoot_SS_Portal_Admin\SP_SP_00_00| Self-Service Portal]. *''Project Accountant'': A user with this role can upload and process GL and PM transactions for project tasks with the ''Completed'', ''Canceled'', or ''In Planning'' status, while all other users are not able to process transactions for such project tasks. *''ReportDesigner'': A user with this role can publish reports in Acumatica ERP. Any user can create reports in Report Designer, but for publishing reports in Acumatica ERP, the user needs to be granted this role. *''TX Admin'': A user with this role has access to functions and settings related to taxes. *''TX Viewer'': A user with this role has read-only access to tax-related functions. *''Wiki Admin'': A user with this role can set other users&rsquo; access rights to wikis. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management]. *''Wiki Author'': A user with this role can create wiki articles. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management].
==Guest Roles== Users from outside your organization may need access to your Acumatica ERP instance if they are partners or customers of your organization. We recommend that they access necessary data through Acumatica Self-Service Portal. You can perform the following steps to provide external users with the rights to use Acumatica Self-Service Portal: [anchor|#_93f4fbee-d751-4cae-a090-48e843273ead] #You create a contact-related user type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_25_00|User Types] ([~/?ScreenId=EP202500|EP202500]) form, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Add_Contact_User_Type|To Add a User Type]. #You add at least one user role with the '''Guest Role''' check box selected in the list of allowed roles of the created user type. You can use the built-in ''Portal User'' role or create a new one. #You assign the external user account with the created user type, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Create_User_Account|To Create a Local User Account].
For more information, see [HelpRoot_SS_Portal_Admin\SP__mng_Access|Managing Access to Self-Service Portal]. ==Roles and Access Rights== In Acumatica ERP, you can control a role&rsquo;s access to system entities, from the workspace level, which is the most broad, down to the form element level, which is the most specific. The available levels of access depend on the system entity type. For more information about configuring access rights, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role_Configuration|Access Rights for Roles]. ==An Example of Roles and Access Rights== Consider an example of some roles a business might set, as shown in the illustration below (with full or ''Delete'' access rights shown in blue and ''View Only'' access rights shown in purple): [anchor|#ul_q42_mfn_gk] *''Accountant'': Allows its members full access to journal entries and schedules, and limited (''View Only'') access to allocations. *''AR Administrator'': Allows its members full access to accounts receivable documents; these members may also view accounts payable documents and budgets. *''AP Administrator'': Allows its members full access to accounts payable documents; in addition, users with the role may view accounts receivable documents and budgets. *''Accounting Manager'': Allows its members full access to allocations and budgets; these members may view other user accounts too. *''Security Officer'': Allows its members full access rights to user accounts, roles, and restriction groups. Roles and User Access to Entities[anchor|#image_kbh_v1t_th][image:UserGuide/Images/Role-Based_Access_Roles_access.gif|popup|250px] Note that some users have only one role assigned, while other users have multiple roles, in accordance with their responsibilities. A user&rsquo;s access to an entity is defined by the most permissive level of access among the roles assigned to this user. With the roles shown here, User 6 (with both the ''Accounting Manager'' and ''AP Administrator'' roles assigned) has full access to budgets from the ''Accounting Manager'' role, rather than view-only access from the ''AP Administrator'' role. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role_Configuration|Access Rights for Roles] *[HelpRoot_Dev_Customization\CG_GL_Stages_Role|To Assign the Customizer Role to a User Account] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Roles_and_Access_Rights|Levels of Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Managing_Field_Level_Audit_Access|Management of Access to Field-Level Audit Functionality] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Support_of_Multiple_Companies|Support of Multiple Tenants] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Add_Contact_User_Type|To Add a User Type] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Create_User_Account|To Create a Local User Account] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) *[HelpRoot_SS_Portal_Admin\SP_SP_00_00| Self-Service Portal] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005])

In Acumatica ERP access rights can be set to particular system objects: forms, containers (of form elements), form elements, and wikis.{br}
To restrict the access rights that users have to system objects, you assign users ''roles'', as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access]. For example, suppose that you define the ''Junior Accountant'' and ''Senior Accountant'' roles. Users with both roles will work with the forms related to accounts payable. Users with the ''Junior Accountant'' role assigned can only enter bills, while users with the ''Senior Accountant'' role assigned can enter bills and approve them for payment. {br}
There are two ways to set up access rights for roles in Acumatica ERP:[anchor|#_cf00f343-8e1a-493c-ae8a-7d5f255901a0] *To set up access rights for a particular role to multiple system objects, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) form. For example, you use this way when you have created a new role and want to set up access to all necessary forms for it. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Access_Rights_by_Role_Configuration|To Configure Access Rights for a Selected User Role]. *To set up access rights to a particular system object for multiple roles, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) form. You use this way primarily when you want to configure access rights workspace by workspace, or form by form. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Access_Rights_by_Screen_Configuration|To Configure Access Rights to System Objects].
The specific levels of access rights to system objects you select for roles depend on the object type for which you are specifying access rights. For some objects, you can only permit or deny access, but for others you can set up partial access (for example, view-only access). For details about levels of access rights for system objects in Acumatica ERP, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Roles_and_Access_Rights|Levels of Access Rights].[anchor|#_3cdf7488-d72b-468c-b640-c82a84cda4f3]((({S:Warn}You have to be very careful when you assign multiple roles to a user account because these roles may have different levels of access rights to system objects. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Roles_and_Access_Rights#_2708bbea-95b1-4a47-8cc5-3bbcb3dc961f|Access Rights Level for a User Account]. ))) You can set the access each role has to the wikis available in your company by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_15|Wiki Access by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202015|SM202015]) form. To view and update the map of any wiki, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_10|Wiki Site Map] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202010|SM202010]) form. For details about managing access to wikis, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management].{br}
This topic describes the most common tasks of access rights configuration.{br}{TOC} == Initial Setup of Access Rights== After you have installed Acumatica ERP and created user roles, all roles that you have created have the ''Not Set'' access level set to all forms. The nested objects (containers and elements) have the ''Inherited'' access level. [anchor|#_8c4725fa-1fab-4e32-b2b8-511e411750a8]((({S:Danger}The ''Not Set'' access level indicates that all roles have access to the forms until at least one role is assigned the ''Revoked'' or ''Granted'' access rights. This role can be any role in the system. All roles with the ''Not Set'' level are then denied access to the form. ))) You need to set up the access rights that roles have to the system objects that will be used by users with the roles in their work. The most frequent scenarios of access rights setup are the following:[anchor|#_1b65e78f-d81d-412d-bdee-2103a4e118cd] *The role should have access to all forms within a particular workspace (or particular workspaces). For example, suppose that chief accountants should work with all the forms related to the financial functionality. These forms are grouped into several workspaces. For the role you define for chief accountants, you can specify the access rights level to a system object at the workspace level, and the system will automatically apply this access rights level to all nested objects. For a detailed procedure, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Initial_Access_Rights_Configuration|To Initially Configure Access Rights]. *Users with the role should work with particular forms. For example, suppose that junior accountants should work only with particular forms within the '''Payables''' workspace. For the role you set up for these accountants, you need to set up access rights to the nested system objects manually. For a detailed procedure, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Access_Rights_by_Role_Configuration|To Configure Access Rights for a Selected User Role]. [anchor|#section_wgv_hbd_yl] ==Management of Access Rights== During ongoing maintenance of Acumatica ERP, you may have tasks to change roles&rsquo; access rights to some system objects. You can change these access rights in different ways, depending on your task, as shown in the following examples:[anchor|#_fffb2a7c-2b1a-4dbf-bbce-ef93b13f91ed] *If you want users with a particular role to work with all forms within a workspace or multiple workspaces (for example, users with the ''Chief Accountant'' role should have access to all the workspaces related to the financial functionality). For the role, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) form, you set the ''Granted'' access level for all needed workspaces, and the system will automatically set the ''Delete'' access level for all forms and the ''Granted'' access level for all reports within the workpaces. *If you want to hide all forms that belong to a workspace from users with a particular role so these users cannot work with the forms of the workspace (for example, warehouse workers should work only with the inventory and order management functionality and view Help; these users should not see the forms in other workspaces in the system). For the role, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) form, you set the ''Revoked'' access rights level for all the workspaces to whose forms you want to restrict access. The system hides from the main menu workspaces within which the ''Revoked'' level is set to all forms. *Suppose that you want to permit access to a particular form for a particular role so that a user with the role can access this form from another form. For example, a user with the ''Junior System Administrator'' role should not have access to the workspaces that relate to company organization, but the user needs to use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CR_30_20_00|Contacts] ([~/?ScreenId=CR302000|CR302000]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_30_00|Employees] ([~/?ScreenId=EP203000|EP203000]) forms to create user accounts. (For details on user accounts creation, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_User_Accounts|User Accounts in Acumatica ERP].) In this case, for the role, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) form, you set the ''Revoked'' access rights level to the related workspaces and the ''Delete'' access level to the forms. The system displays restricted workspaces in the main menu, but only links to allowed forms are visible inside a workspace. *If you want to restrict access to a particular form element (for example, only a user with the ''Chief Accountant'' role can release documents on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_20_00|Payments and Applications] ([~/?ScreenId=AR302000|AR302000]) form), you set the ''Edit'' access rights level to this element for the role that should use it, and the ''Revoked'' access rights level for all roles that should not use it. *If you need to reset access rights for a user role to all forms, you can reset access rights to ''Not Set'' for this role to all workspaces; the system will automatically apply the access level to all nested objects. For a detailed procedure, [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Reset_Access_Rights|To Reset Access Rights to All Forms in a Workspace]. *If you want to configure a role for the users who will be working with wikis, including Help wiki, you give the role access to the following: **The wiki-related forms by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) or [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) form **The wiki articles by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_15|Wiki Access by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202015|SM202015]) form *:For details about managing access to wikis, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management].
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Roles_and_Access_Rights|Levels of Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Role-Based_Access|Role-Based Access] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Access_Rights_by_Role_Configuration|To Configure Access Rights for a Selected User Role] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Initial_Access_Rights_Configuration|To Initially Configure Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Access_Rights_by_Screen_Configuration|To Configure Access Rights to System Objects] *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Reset_Access_Rights|To Reset Access Rights to All Forms in a Workspace] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_15|Wiki Access by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202015|SM202015])

With Acumatica ERP, you can control access to system objects at broad and granular levels, down to the control of form elements, such as buttons, text boxes, and check boxes. Users are assigned to roles, and you give these roles the appropriate levels of access rights (or access levels) to system objects— forms, containers of form elements, form elements, and wikis.[anchor|#_9c93d4f1-c032-4248-8ee7-68716483c3c2]((({S:Warn}You have to be very careful when you assign multiple roles to a user account because these roles may have different levels of access rights to system objects. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Roles_and_Access_Rights#_2708bbea-95b1-4a47-8cc5-3bbcb3dc961f|Access Rights Level for a User Account]. ))) You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) forms to manage access rights. For more information about access rights, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights].{br}
You can set the access each role has to the wikis available in your company by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_15|Wiki Access by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202015|SM202015]) form. To view and update the map of any wiki, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_10|Wiki Site Map] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202010|SM202010]) form. For details about managing access to wikis, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management].{br}
This topic describes the levels of access rights available to system objects.{br}{TOC} ==Access Rights at the Workspace Level== In Acumatica ERP, you do not set up access to a particular workspace itself. Instead, by setting access rights at the workspace level, you set up access for all the nested objects. If you change the access level to any nested object of a workspace, the system will change the access level to ''Multiple Rights'' at the workspace level. {br}
The system displays a workspace with the ''Multiple Rights'' level in the main menu. On the workspace dashboard, the system displays only forms for which access is not restricted for a particular user.{br}
Keep in mind that a form may belong to multiple workspaces. If you set an access level to one of these workspaces (that is, to all forms in the workspace), the system will assign to a form that belongs to multiple workspaces the access level set most recently for one of these workspaces. The system will then change the access level for other workspaces to which the form belongs to the ''Multiple Rights'' option, if these workspaces had a different access level. For example, the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_40_20_00|Vendor Details] form can be accessed from the '''Payables''' and '''Purchases''' workspaces. Both workspaces have the ''Granted'' access level for the ''Purchasing'' role. You change an access level for the form under the '''Payables''' workspace to ''Revoked''. The system displays the new access level of the form under the '''Purchases''' workspace and changes access level to ''Multiple Rights'' for both workspaces.{br}
The following table summarizes the levels of access rights that roles can have to all forms that belong to a particular workspace of Acumatica ERP.[anchor|#table_fzs_pqd_wj] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Multiple Rights'' | Means that a role has different access levels to the nested objects of a workspace. If you change the access level for the workspace, the system will automatically apply the new level to all nested objects. |- | ''Not Set'' | Allows all roles to have access to all forms in a workspace until ''Revoked'' or ''Granted'' access level is set to the workspace for at least one role. After that, a role with this level is denied access to the forms in the workspace. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to all the forms in a workspace; for users with the role, the workspace and its forms do not appear in the main menu. |- | ''Granted'' | Allows the role access to all the forms in a workspace. You can, however, limit or revoke access to particular forms within the workspace for the role. In this case, the system will change the access level for the workspace to ''Multiple Rights''. |}((({S:Warn}You can set up access rights to individual forms in the '''Hidden''' node (which cannot be accessed from the main menu), but not to the node itself. ))) You can reset a role&rsquo;s access level at the workspace level (that is, the access level to all the forms in a workspace) to ''Not Set'' any time you want. For a procedure that describes how to reset access rights, see [HelpRoot_Administration\US__how_Reset_Access_Rights|To Reset Access Rights to All Forms in a Workspace].[anchor|#section_whj_vn2_wj] ==Access Rights at the Form Level== Within each workspace, you can set the access rights that roles have to Acumatica ERP forms, which affects what users with those roles can access. The level of access rights to the form is inherited by the entities and records that can be created by using the form. You can set any of the following levels of access rights to forms. [anchor|#table_y1t_pqd_wj] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Not Set'' | When assigned to all roles, allows all roles to have access to the form until access rights are set to any other level for at least one role. After at least one role has been assigned another level of access rights, access to the form is denied for a role with this access level. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to the form and its functionality. |- | ''View Only'' | Gives the role restricted access to the form and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the form and any records associated with the form (in drop-down lists on other forms). This level forbids users with the role to edit details about any record, create new records or entities of the type, and delete records. |- | ''Edit'' | Gives the role restricted access to the form and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the form, select records, and edit details about any record. This level forbids users with the role to create new records or entities of the type, and to delete records.The '''Clipboard''' button is available on the form toolbar for users with the role. |- | ''Insert'' | Gives the role restricted access to the form and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the form, select records, edit details about any record, and create new records or entities of the type. This level forbids users with the role to delete records.The '''Clipboard''' and '''Insert''' buttons are available on the form toolbar for users with the role. |- | ''Delete'' | Gives the role complete access to the form and its functionality. This level encompasses the capabilities of the ''View Only'', ''Edit'', and ''Insert'' levels, while also giving users with the role the ability to delete records. For users with the role, the '''Clipboard''', '''Insert''', and '''Delete''' buttons are available on the form toolbar. |} By default, a new role has the ''Not Set'' access level.{br}
If you change access rights for a user role to a form or a form element, your changes affect only this form or form element. To make the form available in the navigation pane to a user with this role, set the access level for the form to the ''View Only'' level or more permissive. ==Access Rights to Containers of Form Elements== Each form includes containers of elements, such as nested forms, tabs, and grids. Each container includes multiple elements and actions. You can restrict access to any of these containers on the form. The level of access rights a role has to the container is inherited by the entities and records created by using the container, if applicable. For example, if you permit access for a user role to a grid, a user with this role can access all records in this grid. By default, containers inherit access level from the form to which they belong. You can set any of the following levels of access rights to the containers.{br}
[anchor|#_8832ae06-4664-4c72-b270-6012730a91aa] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Inherited'' | Indicates that the role&rsquo;s access to the container is inherited from its access level to the form. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to the container and hides it from the form for users with the role. These users will not see the container on the form. |- | ''View Only'' | Gives the role restricted access to the container and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the container and any records associated with the container (in drop-down lists on other forms), if applicable. The level forbids users with the role to edit details about any record, create new records or entities of the type, and delete records, if applicable. |- | ''Edit'' | Gives users with the role restricted access to the container and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the container, select records, and edit details about any record, if applicable. The level forbids users with the role to create new records or entities of the type, and delete records, if applicable. |- | ''Insert'' | Gives the role restricted access to the container and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the container, select records, edit details about any record, and create new records or entities of the type, if applicable. This level forbids users with the role to delete records, if applicable. |- | ''Delete'' | Gives the role complete access to the container and its functionality. This level encompasses the capabilities of the ''View Only'', ''Edit'', and ''Insert'' levels, while also giving users with the role the ability to delete records, if applicable. |} ==Access Rights to Form Elements== By default, a role&rsquo;s access rights to the form elements and actions are inherited from the role&rsquo;s access level to the container of form elements to which elements and actions belong. Thus, you should set the role&rsquo;s access level to the container of form elements before setting an access level to an element or an action. Then you can set access rights to the form elements and actions. You can set up the following levels of access rights to form elements.[anchor|#table_kgx_3h2_wj] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Inherited'' | Indicates that the role&rsquo;s access level to the element is inherited from its access level to the container of form elements. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to the element and hides the element. A user with the role will not see the element on the form. |- | ''View Only'' | Makes the element read-only for users with the role. A user with the role will see the element on the form but will not be able to use it. |- | ''Edit'' | Allows the use of the element for users with the role. |} If a particular form toolbar contains form-specific buttons, you can deny access for the role to these buttons, by setting ''Revoked'' for the buttons. You can revoke access to some of the elements to hide their contents from users with ''View Only'' access level. ((({S:Hint}Configuring a role&rsquo;s access rights at the form control level requires in-depth knowledge of Acumatica ERP functionality. )))[anchor|#_2708bbea-95b1-4a47-8cc5-3bbcb3dc961f] ==Access Rights Level for a User Account== The level of access rights a user account has to a system object is defined by the user roles assigned to the user. If a user has multiple roles assigned and the roles have different access levels to the system object, the following general rule is used: Acumatica ERP applies the most permissive access level among the roles. For example, suppose that a user is assigned the ''Employee'' and ''Sales Manager'' roles. The ''Employee'' role has the ''Revoked'' access level at the '''Inventory''' workspace level, and the ''Sales Manager'' role has the ''Granted'' access level at the same level. With these settings, the user has the ''Granted'' access level to the forms in the '''Inventory''' workspace.{br}
The algorithm of calculating access rights differs from the general rule described in the previous paragraph for a user with multiple roles assigned, some or all of which have the ''Inherited'' access level (which is applied to form element containers and form elements by default). For this user, the following rules are used to calculate access rights to a form element container or form element:{br}
[anchor|#_1531e08b-650b-4e5c-8952-2de11b28aa2a] *If all roles have the ''Inherited'' access level to the particular form element container or form element, the resulting access level is the most permissive access level of the system object at the next highest level—the form (for a form element container) or the form element container (for a form element). *If you have explicitly specified an access level to the particular form element container or form element for at least one role, while the other roles have the ''Inherited'' access level to this system object, then the resulting level of access rights is the most permissive access level among only the roles with explicitly defined access levels. The system ignores the roles with the ''Inherited'' level of access rights. This algorithm is used to optimize the speed of loading the form. {br}
The following examples illustrate the system behavior described in this section: [anchor|#_a1d81239-dffc-44cf-b21e-79f4022c8978] #Suppose that a user is assigned the ''Employee'' and the ''Accountant'' user roles. The ''Employee'' role has the ''Revoked'' access level to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_30_00|Customers] ([~/?ScreenId=AR303000|AR303000]) form, and the ''Accountant'' role has the ''Edit'' access level to this form. The default access level both roles have to the form elements is ''Inherited''. The user with these roles, then, has the ''Edit'' access level to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_30_00|Customers] form and its elements. #Suppose that a user is assigned the ''Employee'' and ''Accountant'' user roles. Both roles have the ''Insert'' access level to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_10_00|Invoices and Memos] ([~/?ScreenId=AR301000|AR301000]) form. You have decided to forbid users with the ''Accountant'' role to release invoices. For the ''Accountant'' role, you specify the ''Revoked'' access level for the '''Release''' button on this form. The ''Employee'' role has the ''Inherited'' access level to the '''Release''' button. With the settings you have specified, the user has the ''Revoked'' access level to the '''Release''' button. #Suppose that a user is assigned the ''Employee'', ''Warehouse Worker'', and ''Sales Assistant'' user roles. All these roles have the ''Insert'' access level to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\IN_30_10_00|Receipts] ([~/?ScreenId=IN301000|IN301000]) form. The ''Employee'' role has the ''Inherited'' access level to the '''Release''' button on this form, the ''Warehouse Worker'' role has the ''Revoked'' access level to this button, and the ''Sales Assistant'' role has the ''View Only'' access level to this button. As a result, the user has the ''View Only'' access level (the most permissive level of the two explicitly defined levels) to this button.
You can view the user access level for a particular form, containers or form element by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_55|Access Rights by User] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201055|SM201055]) form. On the form, you select the user account for which you want to view the access level. In the left pane, you select a node that contains the nested objects (forms or form elements) you are interested in. Then in the right pane, you select the form or container and click the '''View Roles''' button on the pane toolbar. The system opens the '''View Roles''' dialog box, where you can view the access rights of the user to the selected object in the '''Computed Access Rights''' column. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\US__con_Access_Rights|User Access Rights] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025])

In Acumatica ERP, the business date is displayed in the info area. The business date is the date that the system will insert by default into the records that you add to the system. {br}

By default, the current date is set as the business date. If the ''Secure Business Date'' feature is disabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form, all users can change the business date by clicking the Business Date menu button in the info area. If the ''Secure Business Date'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form, users can change the business date only if the ''BusinessDateOverride'' role is assigned to them.{br}{TOC}
==Configuring Permissions to Change the Business Date==
Some companies might want to restrict the availability of changing the business date in the system. This can be done to avoid issues with generated documents that have the dates of closed periods inserted into them. {br}

By default, all users can change the business date in the Acumatica ERP system. To restrict the availability to change it, you should enable the ''Secure Business Date'' feature on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. This will make the Business Date menu button generally unavailable for clicking and editing.{br}

In your company, only some employees might need the ability to change the business date in the system. You can grant these users access rights to change it by assigning the ''BusinessDateOverride'' role to them on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_10|Users] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201010|SM201010]) form or the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form.((({S:Warn}This role is available only if the ''Secure Business Date'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form.
)))
==Incrementing of the Business Date==
The system handles the incrementing of the business date at midnight individually for each user session: The date is automatically incremented at midnight only if you have not modified the business date in any way during your user session. {br}

That is, if you do not change the business date during your user session and your session is active at midnight, the system increments the date. If you have modified the business date somehow, the system will keep the changed date as long as your user session is active.
