==Tenants== When you install the Acumatica ERP application, you create at least one tenant. You can create more tenants with the help of the Acumatica ERP Configuration Wizard, or directly from the Acumatica ERP application by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. Because the functionality of creating new tenants is available within the application, you can create multiple tenants in the same application without signing out of the application. For details on creating tenants, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MultiCompany_Add_Company|To Add a New Tenant by Using the Web Interface].((({S:Warn}We recommend that before you create the second and next tenants you open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_25|Space Usage] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203525|SM203525]) form and make sure that you have enough free space in the Acumatica ERP database. ))) You can configure each tenant from scratch or create tenants by using templates based on snapshots. For more information on using snapshots as tenant templates, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Company_Templates|Snapshots as Tenant Templates]. Once the tenant is configured, users can initialize it by importing or entering the data. A tenant&rsquo;s configuration settings and entered data are not accessible from other tenants of the same application. ==Active and Test Tenants== You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_30|Tenant List] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203530|SM203530]) form to view the list of tenants and the statuses of the tenants (that is, if the tenant is active, test, or unlicensed) and the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form to add, delete, and manage particular tenants.{br}
''Active'' tenants are the tenants that have the ''Active'' status and are used in the production environment. Your license determines the number of active tenants you can add to the instance, the number of concurrent users allowed, and the set of features you can activate for the instance. {br}
''Test'' tenants are the tenants that have the ''Test'' status. You can create a virtually unlimited number of test tenants because the test tenants do not count toward the maximum number of allowed tenants, based on your license. At the same time, all test tenants have the following limitations:[anchor|#ul_ipd_2xg_ks] *Only two concurrent users are allowed *A test tenant cannot be converted back to an active tenant
You can use test tenants in a test environment for the following purposes:[anchor|#ul_yzg_wdn_nm] *To test application features in a demo tenant. You can try any application feature in a tenant with demo data. *To test whether specific configuration changes are applicable to the tenant configuration. *To train your employees through a copy of a live tenant.
For details on setting up a test environment, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Test_Environment|Configuration of the Test Environment]. [anchor|#_55903026-815a-4006-ba6a-52e31388461b] ==The System Tenant== When you install Acumatica ERP, the System tenant (with a '''Tenant ID''' set to ''1'') is always created automatically. {br}
The System tenant contains the preconfigured system data, such as roles, numbering sequences, and the wiki-based documentation. The system data is used by all tenants of the same application instance. {br}
By default, the System tenant is hidden on all end-user forms. All other user-created tenants inherit the initial configuration and system data (predefined data) from the System tenant. That is, all the data available in System tenant is visible to other tenants in the same database. An application update or upgrade replaces all data available in the System tenant, while the data created by users in user-created tenants remains unchanged. {br}
A snapshot created for a user-defined tenant includes all custom data available in the database for the tenant account and does not include any data contained in the System tenant. When a snapshot is being restored in the same database or another database, it uses the system data from the System tenant available in that database. [anchor|#_00438cad-c503-4843-b289-a4e202879e79] ==The Parent Tenant== If you would like to replace the preconfigured roles, numbering sequences, and other data similarly for multiple new tenants, you can create a ''parent'' tenant that will serve as a system tenant for your new tenants. {br}
To configure a custom parent tenant, create a new tenant and provide a name that clearly indicates how this tenant will be used (for example, ''MyParent''). This tenant inherits all the data from the System tenant. In the MyParent tenant, override the preconfigured settings as needed and specify other configuration settings to be used in all the new tenants. Then when you create a new tenant by using the Acumatica ERP Configuration Wizard, you specify MyParent as the new tenant&rsquo;s parent tenant; the new tenant will inherit all the data from the MyParent tenant, not the System tenant. You can create a virtually unlimited number of parent tenants; a parent tenant can be a child of another parent tenant. Users won&rsquo;t be able to sign in to a parent tenant.((({S:Warn}You can create new tenants based on the parent tenant only by using the Acumatica ERP Configuration Wizard. ))) If you create a snapshot of a tenant based on a custom parent that is not the System tenant, this snapshot will not contain the parent&rsquo;s data; when the snapshot is restored in another database with no custom parent tenant, the custom parent&rsquo;s data will be replaced by the original system data. To fully restore such a tenant from its snapshot in another database, perform the following steps: #Create the first new tenant. #Restore the snapshot of the parent tenant in the first new tenant. This tenant will serve as the custom parent tenant. #Create the second new tenant, and select the first tenant as the parent tenant for the second tenant. #Restore the tenant snapshot with all the required data in this new tenant. [anchor|#_aef32d79-655d-4926-9ad3-0cab76a0d85a] ==Signing in to a Specific Tenant== In a multitenant Acumatica ERP instance, the Tenant box appears on Sign-In page by default. Thus, the users can select the tenant to sign in to from the list of all available tenants.{br}
If you want to restrict the list of tenants a user can see only to the tenants the user has access to, select the '''Secure Tenant on Login Screen''' check box on the Tenant Setup page of the Acumatica ERP Configuration Wizard. In this case, the '''Tenant''' box does not appear on the Sign-In page by default and all users first authenticate themselves by entering their login and password. Depending on the user, one of the following occurs:[anchor|#_5b6af4ed-9f91-48c8-a1bb-6cfb0f0d0b6c] *A user who has access to only one tenant will be automatically signed in to this tenant after entering the login and password. *A user who has access to multiple tenants and has the same credentials in these tenants must select a tenant in the Tenant box, which appears after the user has been authenticated and contains the list of tenants available for the user. *A user who has access to multiple tenants and has different credentials for different tenants is signed in to the tenant whose credentials the user entered on the Sign-In page. *A user who has access to multiple tenants and logs in to Acumatica ERP instance using single sign-on with an external identity provider, is signed in to the first tenant with enabled single sign-on.
==Data Sharing Between Tenants== Acumatica ERP provides shared data access in a multitenant configuration. You can set up the data sharing mode for all tenants on a per-table basis and the mode is applied to every tenant immediately. ((({S:Hint}Table configuration is a dangerous operation that can result in database corruption. Any changes you make are at your own risk. If you configure tables, be sure to first back up the database. ))) You can select one of the available data sharing modes: ''Split'', ''Shared'', or ''Separate''. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Test_Environment|Configuration of the Test Environment] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Company_Templates|Snapshots as Tenant Templates] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Company_Snapshots|Tenant Snapshots] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MultiCompany_Add_Company|To Add a New Tenant by Using the Web Interface]

If you need to create multiple similar tenants, you don&rsquo;t have to configure each tenant from scratch as described in the Acumatica ERP Implementation Guide. To speed up the implementation of new tenants, you can create and use tenant templates. In Acumatica ERP, you use the functionality of snapshots to create tenant templates.{br}
You create snapshots by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. A ''snapshot'' may contain all custom data available in the database for the tenant account or only some of the data. For details on snapshots, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__mng_Snapshots|Managing Snapshots].{br}
When a tenant snapshot is restored in a newly created empty tenant, this new tenant will contain all the data that you included in the snapshot. You can restore a snapshot in the same database where it was created or import it to another website and restore it in another database. Any snapshot can be used multiple times. {br}
This topic outlines several possible method of using snapshots as tenant templates. {br}{TOC} ==Method I== To create a new tenant that is very similar in configuration to an existing tenant without any customizations, follow the basic steps below: ((({S:Warn}A snapshot carries information about the version of the database where it was created, so before you restore a snapshot, make sure that the versions match. )))[anchor|#ol_xhm_lqs_tr] #Sign in to the tenant you want to use as a template #Take a snapshot of the tenant and do the following on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] form: #*In the '''Export mode''' box, select ''Settings only'' to include the tenant&rsquo;s configuration settings only and exclude actual documents. #*Select the '''Prepare Data for Export''' check box. #:For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Add|To Take a Snapshot]. #Export the snapshot, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Export|To Export a Snapshot]. #Sign in to the new the tenant. #Import the prepared snapshot without customization data, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Import|To Import a Snapshot]. #Restore the data from the snapshot, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Restore|To Restore a Snapshot].
After the snapshot is restored, the new tenant has the same settings as the source tenant does. ==Method II== If you need to create multiple related tenants with similar configurations, first configure the most typical one (which you will use as a prototype). At each stage of implementation, create a snapshot that includes the full data of the prototype tenant. If the tenants are related businesses, you can enter business accounts that are used by more than one tenant and add them to another snapshot that can be used for each tenant. {br}
When you create a snapshot, it appears on the list of available snapshots for the tenant on the '''Snapshots''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] form. Snapshots of a specific tenant, by default, are visible to (and can be restored in) only this tenant. However, if needed, you can change the visibility of the snapshots to allow these snapshots to be visible to (and restored in) other tenants in the same database. When you create another related tenant, select the snapshot to be used as a template for the new tenant by following these guidelines: *Select a snapshot of a later stage of implementation if the new tenant is very similar to the prototype. *Select a snapshot that features an earlier implementation stage if the new tenant is similar to the prototype only at some extent (to include only those configuration features that present in the new tenant).
==Method III== Suppose you need to create multiple related tenants for which you need to replace some preconfigured settings (such as roles and numbering sequences), add custom reports and inquiries, and customize specific forms similarly. Preconfigured settings are provided by the System tenant, which is available in each installation as a hidden tenant with tenant ID ''1''. These settings are available to each tenant created in the same database. {br}
You can create a custom ''parent'' tenant that contains all the data that is shared between these tenants. To configure a custom parent tenant, perform the following general steps: #Create the tenant that will contain the shared data. #Change the preconfigured settings as needed, and configure other functionality that will be used in all tenants. #Take a snapshot of the tenant and do the following on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] form: #*In the '''Export mode''' box, select ''Full'' to include the tenant&rsquo;s configuration settings only and exclude actual documents. #*Select the '''Prepare Data for Export''' check box. #:For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Add|To Take a Snapshot]. #Create a new tenant in the same instance of application by using the Acumatica ERP Configuration Wizard. Specify the configured tenant as the parent for the new tenant; the new tenant will inherit all the data from the parent tenant. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\Managing_Companies_Add_new|To Add a New Tenant by Using Acumatica ERP Configuration Wizard] in Acumatica ERP Installation Guide. #Repeat Step 4 to add as many new tenants as needed, all based on the custom parent tenant.
If you want to create a similar tenant in another instance of application by using the snapshot of a tenant based on the custom parent tenant, you first restore the parent tenant from its snapshot. Then you create a new empty tenant based on this custom parent tenant, and restore the snapshot with actual tenant data. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Company_Snapshots|Tenant Snapshots] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_05|Update Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203505|SM203505]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_10|Apply Updates] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203510|SM203510])

Protecting data is very important for every business. Thus, before you make any significant configuration changes or perform an irreversible operation, you should perform the required changes in a test environment—that is, a test tenant that contains the full or partial data of your tenant. If you have applied the changes to the test tenant successfully, only then you should apply them to your live tenant. {br}
Also, the test tenants can also be used for training: Users can try the system and train to perform all operations on the test tenant without affecting the live tenant. For more information on test tenants, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Support_of_Multiple_Companies|Support of Multiple Tenants]. ==Test Tenant Setup== Acumatica ERP provides functionality that you can use to set up a test tenant. You can copy the data of the whole tenant to a test tenant, or copy only partial data by using snapshots. A test environment can be set up in the following stages: [anchor|#ol_mny_gl5_zh] #Create a new tenant, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MultiCompany_Add_Company|To Add a New Tenant by Using the Web Interface]. #Change the new tenant to test tenant, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MiltiCompany_Convert_to_test|To Convert a Tenant to the Test Tenant]. #Populate the tenant with data in one of the following ways: #*Configure the tenant from scratch #*Restore a snapshot of an existing tenant to the new tenant. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Company_Templates|Snapshots as Tenant Templates]. #*In a multitenant configuration, copy the data of an existing tenant into the new tenant. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MultiCompany_Copy_Company|To Copy an Existing Tenant].
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MiltiCompany_Convert_to_test|To Convert a Tenant to the Test Tenant] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_MultiCompany_Copy_Company|To Copy an Existing Tenant]

You can use test tenants to train your staff or test the results of irreversible operations before performing such operations on your production tenant. You can have a virtually unlimited number of test tenants in your instance. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__mng_MultiCompany|Managing Tenants] and [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Test_Environment|Configuration of the Test Environment].{br}
