System email accounts for outgoing mail are used mainly to send mass emails for campaigns or mailing lists, or for automatic replies to incoming mail. When users involved with CRM activities create a mass email by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CR_30_80_00|Mass Emails] ([~/?ScreenId=CR308000|CR308000]) form, they can select in the '''From''' box the system email account to which they have access (for details, see [HelpRoot_CRM\CR__con_Mass_Mail|Mass Emails]). When a user clicks '''Send''' on the form toolbar, the SMTP server associated with the selected system email account generates each message of the mass email in accordance with the specified template and replaces placeholders in the email properties and the message body with the data of one of the recipients on the list, until the complete mailing list is processed. However, no emails are actually sent as a result of this process.{br}

To initiate the sending of outgoing emails, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_10|Send and Receive Email] ([~/?ScreenId=SM507010|SM507010]) form. To send the emails selectively, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_00|Emails Pending Processing] ([~/?ScreenId=SM507000|SM507000]) form. {br}

Once the system accounts are configured, you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_10|Send and Receive Email] ([~/?ScreenId=SM507010|SM507010]) form to initiate the receipt of incoming emails and schedule the operations of sending and receiving mail. To process selected incoming and outgoing emails, use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_00|Emails Pending Processing] ([~/?ScreenId=SM507000|SM507000]) form.{br}

To allow the system to automatically resend outgoing emails whose processing has failed, you can use the '''Automatic Resend Attempts''' setting on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_01|Email Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204001|SM204001]) form. This setting defines the number of times that the scheduled processing is allowed to fail for an email before the email's status changes from ''Pending Processing'' to ''Failed''. However, the system ignores this setting if a critical error (that is, an error whose code starts with 5, such as 550) occurs on the mail server or if you run the processing manually.((({S:Hint}You can suspend the operations of sending and receiving emails for all system email accounts at once by selecting the '''Suspend Email Processing''' check box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_01|Email Preferences] form. You may need to do this if you have troubles with your mail servers and need to suspend all operations on these servers to diagnose the problem.
)))

Over time, system email accounts may accumulate an extremely large number of emails, both incoming and outgoing, which may result in considerable system slowdown, especially if incoming mail processing has been enabled for these accounts.{br}
In Acumatica ERP, you can archive emails that are too old to be relevant. On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_01|Email Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204001|SM204001]) form, you can enable email archiving by specifying the minimum age of emails to be archived. The actual archiving is performed when you apply this setting to a particular system email account by executing the ''Send All'', ''Receive All'', or ''Send/Receive All'' action, which you can do on any of the following forms:[anchor|#ul_kfs_4m2_dr] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_02|System Email Accounts] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204002|SM204002]): On this form, you can process only one email account at a time. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_10|Send and Receive Email] ([~/?ScreenId=SM507010|SM507010]): On this form, you can process multiple email accounts at once. *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_50_20|Automation Schedules] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205020|SM205020]): You can use this form to create an automation schedule for the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_10|Send and Receive Email] form so that you can regularly process the selected email accounts. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\EM__HOW_To_Create_a_Send_and_Receive_Schedule|To Create a Send and Receive Email Schedule].
Only emails that have the ''Processed'' status can be archived. After the archiving process is completed, the archived emails disappear from the lists on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_00|Incoming] ([~/?ScreenId=CO409000|CO409000]) and [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_80|Sent] ([~/?ScreenId=CO409080|CO409080]) forms; instead, they are all listed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_30|Archived] ([~/?ScreenId=CO409030|CO409030]) form. Thus, archived emails do not get in your way when you are browsing through incoming or outgoing emails, although you still can search for an archived item, or even perform regular actions, such as '''Reply''' or '''Forward''', on it.{br}
Regardless of the settings specified on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_01|Email Preferences] form, you can use the '''Archive''' action on the form toolbar of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_00|Incoming] and [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_80|Sent] forms to archive selected emails at any time. Also, you can archive any email that has the ''Processed'' status by opening it on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CR_30_60_15|Email Activity] ([~/?ScreenId=CR306015|CR306015]) form and using the '''Archive''' action on the form toolbar.((({S:Warn}After it has been archived, an email associated with a particular entity remains listed on the '''Activities''' tab of the respective data entry form. Also, if time tracking has been enabled for this email, the billable time spent on this email (if any) will be billed to the customer even if the email has been archived. (For more information on time tracking for activities, see [HelpRoot_Organization\EP__con_Time_Tracking|Time Activities].) ))) An archived email can be restored from the archive. When it has been restored, the email disappears from the table on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_30|Archived] form and is again listed on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_00|Incoming] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_80|Sent] form, depending on whether it is an incoming or outgoing email; the status of the email changes back to ''Processed''. You can restore an individual email by opening it on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CR_30_60_15|Email Activity] form and clicking '''Actions''' > '''Restore from Archive''' on the form toolbar, or you can restore emails in bulk by selecting these emails in the table on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_30|Archived] form and clicking '''Restore from Archive''' on the form toolbar. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Scheduled_Processing|Scheduled Processing] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_30|Archived] ([~/?ScreenId=CO409030|CO409030]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_01|Email Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204001|SM204001]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_00|Incoming] ([~/?ScreenId=CO409000|CO409000]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_70_10|Send and Receive Email] ([~/?ScreenId=SM507010|SM507010]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\CO_40_90_80|Sent] ([~/?ScreenId=CO409080|CO409080]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_02|System Email Accounts] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204002|SM204002])

After you add a particular type of information (such as business accounts, cases, or opportunities) to the system by using the applicable data entry form, you may want to have a way to view a list of these records. The most convenient way is to configure a substitute form of the inquiry type that will serve as an entry point to the entry form.{br}
With a substitute form, when a user clicks the name of the entry form, the user is automatically redirected to the corresponding substitute form that contains the list of these records in a tabular format. When the user clicks a record, the entry form opens to show the details of the selected record.{br}
This chapter contains information on the configuration and management of the substitute forms in your system. ==In This Chapter==[anchor|#ul_kp1_2y4_ns] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Primary_Screen_As_List|Substitutes for Entry Forms] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_To_Set_Up_Primary_Screen_As_List|To Configure a Generic Inquiry to Replace an Entry Form] *[HelpRoot_Administration\CU__how_PrimaryScreen_Custom|To Replace an Entry Form with a Custom Form] *[HelpRoot_Administration\CU__how_Primary_Screen_Replacement|To Activate the Replacement of an Entry Form] *[HelpRoot_Administration\CU__how_Primary_ScreenReplacement_Cancel|To Cancel the Replacement of an Entry Form]

Sometimes you might need a faster way to access particular information in the system—such as the contacts of a particular vendor or the list of customers. Generally in Acumatica ERP, you can access such information by opening the corresponding data entry or maintenance form and clicking the magnifier icon in the appropriate box; the list of records then opens in the pop-up window. This sequence of events, however, may not give you the information you need quickly enough. The data entry and maintenance forms are convenient for entering new data, but once you have entered most data, you may have a greater need to instead view the list of records created on the data entry form.{br}

In Acumatica ERP, you can create a generic inquiry or custom form that presents the data of a data entry or maintenance form (which is called the ''entry form'' in this context) in a tabular format. The generic inquiry or custom form that you create is called the ''substitute form'' in this context. Once you have created the substitute form, you can replace the entry form with it. Thus, when you click the name of the entry form, you will access the substitute form that contains the list of records. When you click a record name in the list, the entry form (data entry or maintenance) will open.{br}{TOC}
==Configuring a Generic Inquiry to Be Used as a Substitute Form==
To configure a generic inquiry to be used as a substitute form, select the entry form, configure the list of records to be displayed on the substitute form, and then select the place of the form on the site map. You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] ([~/?ScreenId=SM208000|SM208000]) form to configure an inquiry. For an example of configuring a generic inquiry, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\SM__how_How_to_Design_an_Inquiry_In_Inventory|Example: Designing a Generic Inquiry Based on Inventory Data].{br}

If you might need from time to time to add or delete the records in the list (that is, not only view the list of records, but also add records to the system or permanently delete existing records), or make edits to the data shown in the list, you can add the required buttons and menu commands to the form toolbar of the substitute form. You can add any of the following options to a substitute form:[anchor|#ul_ic3_p1c_vp]
*Enabling the creation of new records: If you enable this capability, the '''New Record''' button will be available on the substitute form. When a user clicks the button, the entry form opens to let the user add a new record.
*:((({S:Warn}If you enable the creation of new records on the substitute form, you can define the default values for the fields that appear when you add a record. The system will automatically enter these values in the specified fields when a user adds a new record. You define the default values in the '''New Record Defaults''' table on the '''Entry Point''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] form. 
)))
*Enabling mass removal of records: If you enable mass removal of records, the '''Delete''' button and the '''Selected''' column will be available on the substitute form. A user can select one record or multiple records and then delete them. Additionally, you can configure the system to automatically confirm the deletion of records after this button is clicked and before the records are actually deleted.
*Enabling mass update of records: If you enable this capability, the '''Update''' and '''Update All''' commands will be available in the '''Actions''' menu on the form toolbar and the '''Selected''' column in the table of the substitute form. When you configure this capability, you select the field or fields that should be updated if the user clicks one of these options. A user can select one record or multiple records and then change the specified fields of the selected records.
*Enabling mass actions on records: When you configure this setting, you can select any of the available options according to your needs. The available options depend on the content of the entry form for which you create the inquiry. For example, the following options might be available for the form: ''Copy'', ''Paste'', ''Validate Address'', and ''Mark As Validated''. After you have selected the required options and saved the list, the selected commands will appear in the '''Actions''' menu on the form toolbar and the '''Selected''' column in the table of the substitute form. A user can select one record or multiple records and then apply any available command to the selected records.
*:((({S:Warn}We do not recommend to use mass actions that involve redirecting to other pages, such as Customer Details or Analytical Reports. This scenario may cause performance issues and is not guaranteed to work properly. 
)))

For details on configuring a generic inquiry to be used as a substitute form, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_To_Set_Up_Primary_Screen_As_List|To Configure a Generic Inquiry to Replace an Entry Form].
==Configuring a Custom Form to Be Used as a Substitute Form==
With Acumatica ERP, you can design your own custom forms that you can use to replace the entry forms. Each substitute form must include fields that are mapped to the key fields of the corresponding entry form. For more information on designing custom forms, see [HelpRoot_Dev_Customization\CG_GL_Forms_DevelopCustom|To Develop a Custom Form] in the Customization Guide.{br}

When the custom form is ready, you match the form to the corresponding entry form (that is, specify the entry form that will be replaced with the custom form) by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_85_00|Lists as Entry Points] ([~/?ScreenId=SM208500|SM208500]) form. For details of configuring such a custom form to be used as a substitute form, see [HelpRoot_Administration\CU__how_PrimaryScreen_Custom|To Replace an Entry Form with a Custom Form].
==Accessing Substitute Forms==
In Acumatica ERP, every form has its own level of access that you can configure by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) form. You can change the level of access to the entry and substitute forms independently of each other. However, when a substitute form replaces the corresponding entry form, the substitute form inherits the level of access the users have to the entry form. Thus, to change the level of access users have to the substitute form, you change the level of access to the entry form.{br}

If required, you can cancel the replacement, which involves configuring the system to direct users to the entry form (instead of the substitute form) when they try to open the entry form; canceling the replacement does not involve deleting forms. If you cancel the replacement, the level of access to the substitute form reverts to the initial state (that is, the level of access the substitute form had before you used it to replace an entry form). 
==Replacing the Entry Form with the Substitute Form==
After you have configured a substitute form, you match the substitute form to the corresponding entry form (that is, specify the substitute form that will replace the entry form), with each pair of entry and substitute forms taking its own row on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_85_00|Lists as Entry Points] ([~/?ScreenId=SM208500|SM208500]) form. ((({S:Warn}A generic inquiry is automatically matched to the entry form when you select the entry form in the '''Entry Screen''' box and select the '''Replace Entry Screen with This Inquiry in Menu''' check box on the '''Entry Point''' tab on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] form. The selection on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] form is removed if you delete the row that contains the inquiry on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_85_00|Lists as Entry Points] form.
)))
You can activate or cancel the replacement of any entry form in the list any time you want. Canceling the replacement does not remove the form pair from the list. For details of activating and canceling the replacement of an entry form, see [HelpRoot_Administration\CU__how_Primary_Screen_Replacement|To Activate the Replacement of an Entry Form] and [HelpRoot_Administration\CU__how_Primary_ScreenReplacement_Cancel|To Cancel the Replacement of an Entry Form].{br}

If you delete the row containing the entry form and the corresponding substitute form, you remove the matching between the forms; the replacement is canceled, but the forms are not deleted. 
