e\SM_20_50_20|Automation Schedules] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205020|SM205020]) form. On this form, you configure the schedule by which the system should check the conditions on the data for monitoring. Also, in the '''Screen ID''' box, you must specify the generic inquiry that defines the data for monitoring.
In the '''Raise Event''' box of the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] form, you can also select how the system should generate the business event: for each record that satisfies the trigger conditions or for the whole set of records that satisfy the trigger conditions.{br}
For details on how to configure the system to monitor business events by a schedule, see [HelpRoot_Administration\AI__how_Business_Event_by_Schedule|To Monitor the Business Process Data by a Schedule]. ==An Example of the Business Event Configuration== For example, suppose that you need to configure the system to send a email to the owner of an opportunity when the opportunity is one month from its estimated close date and the opportunity hasn&rsquo;t been updated for more than seven days. You would do the following:[anchor|#_c4d03d62-ce34-4be5-b2b5-138c84734c7c] #Optional: Create a generic inquiry (based on the <tt>PX.Objects.CR.CROpportunity</tt> and <tt>PX.Objects.CR.Contact</tt> tables) that retrieves from the system all opportunities that have the ''Open'' status and an estimated close date that is one month from today&rsquo;s date; the generic inquiry should also retrieve the contact email address of the owner of the respective opportunity. #:((({S:Warn}You could instead use an existing generic inquiry when you define the business event, if one exists that retrieves the needed data. ))) #On the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form, create a business event with the following settings: #*'''Type''': ''Trigger by Schedule'' #* '''Raise Event''': ''For Each Record'' (to make the system generate a business event for each opportunity that satisfies the conditions) #*'''Screen Name''': The generic inquiry you have createdof the ''Trigger by Schedule'' type, and select the generic inquiry you have created in the '''Screen Name''' box. #On the '''Trigger Conditions''' tab, select the following values: #*'''Table Name''': ''Opportunity'' (<tt>PX.Objects.CR.CROpportunity</tt> table) #*'''Field Name''': ''Last Modified Date'' #* '''Condition''': ''Is Less Than'' #* '''Value 1''': ''@Today-7'' #On the '''Subscribers''' tab, select a notification template. You can create a notification template that specifies as the recipient a placeholder for the email address of the owner of the opportunity to be closed. #On the '''Schedules''' tab, create a schedule that is executed every day.
==Business Event Processing== When a business event is configured and is active—that is, the '''Active''' check box is selected for it on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form—and the next schedule execution date comes, the system executes the generic inquiry. If the generic inquiry returns any data, the system checks whether the returned records satisfy the conditions specified on the '''Trigger Conditions''' tab. If there are records that satisfy the conditions (which means that the business event has occurred), the system processes the subscribers of the event that are specified on the '''Subscribers''' tab. {br}
After all subscribers of the business event have been processed, the system saves information about the processing of the business event, which you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form.{br}
The following diagram shows how business events checked for on a schedule are configured and processed.[anchor|#_2732e838-e4cc-4ff9-8765-0c9da2ece6d8][anchor|#_08d1453e-875f-4a0d-8542-dbb7e171fd24][image:UserGuide/Images/BusinessEventBySchedule.png|popup|The processing of a business event monitored on a schedule|450px] ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Administration\AI__con_Business_Event_Subscribers|Subscribers of Business Events] *[HelpRoot_Administration\AI__how_Business_Event_by_Schedule|To Monitor the Business Process Data by a Schedule] *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030])

A subscriber of a business event is an entity in the system (such as an email notification or a script based on an import scenario) that the system processes in a particular way when the business event occurs. In this topic, you can find information about the available types of subscribers.
==Email Notifications==
If a subscriber to a business event is an email notification, when the business event occurs, the system sends an email (or multiple emails) to particular recipients, based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event.{br}

You configure a subscriber of the ''Email Notification'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204003|SM204003]) form. On this form, you must specify the sender, the recipients of the notification emails, and the template for the email message. Also, in the '''Screen''' box, you specify the generic inquiry of the business event. ((({S:Warn}The easiest way to create an email notification for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Email Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] form with the correct value selected in the '''Screen''' box.
)))
In the notification template you define on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] form, you can use placeholders for the values of the form elements. As the placeholders, you can use the data fields available in the results of the generic inquiry of the business event as follows:[anchor|#_c0b0f216-5565-4664-97ef-5327c2504df3]
*To specify the recipients of the emails (in the '''To''', '''CC''', and '''BCC''' boxes), you can use the data fields (as the placeholders, separated with semicolons) that hold email addresses and whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. For example, if you need to monitor cases and send notifications to assignees, you can use a placeholder for the email address of the assignee, such as {{((Contact_eMail))}}. 
*To specify the subject ('''Subject''') of the notification template, you can use any data fields whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs.
*In the body of the notification template (on the '''Message''' tab), you can click '''Insert Data Field''' on the formatting toolbar to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value is retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value was retrieved before the business event occurred. You can use this ability to demonstrate how the value of the data field has changed, for example, a case status has changed from ''New'' to ''Open''.
*In the '''Link to Account''', '''Link to Contact''', and '''Link to Entity''' boxes, you can use the data fields that contain a business account ID, contact ID, or note ID, respectively, and whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. The system creates an activity of the ''Email'' type and links this activity (if any of the values of the specified fields are not empty in the results of the generic inquiry) to the specified business account, contact, or entity. You can then view the activity on the '''Activities''' tab of the corresponding form or in the '''Tasks & Activities''' dialog box, which opens if you click '''Activities''' on the form title bar. For details about activities, see [HelpRoot_CRM\CR__con_Managing_Your_Tasks__Events__and_Activities|Managing Tasks, Events, and Activities].

When the business event occurs and the system processes the subscriber of the ''Email Notification'' type, the system extracts the values of the fields specified for placeholders of the template (from the results of the generic inquiry that satisfy the conditions) and inserts these values into the email. The system then sends the email or emails to the recipients.{br}

If the notification has been sent successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the notification template, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.
==Push Notifications==
If a subscriber to a business event is a push notification, when the business event occurs, the system sends a push notification or multiple push notifications to the mobile devices of particular recipients, based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event.{br}

You configure a subscriber of the ''Mobile Push Notification'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204004|SM204004]) form. On this form, you must specify the push delivery method, the description, the recipients of the notifications, and the template for the message. Also, in the '''Screen''' box, you specify the generic inquiry of the business event. ((({S:Warn}The easiest way to create a push notification for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Mobile Push Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form with the ''Push'' option selected in the '''Delivery Method''' box and the correct value selected in the '''Screen''' box.
)))
In the notification template you define on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form, you can use placeholders for the values of the form elements. As the placeholders, you can use the data fields available in the results of the generic inquiry of the business event as follows:[anchor|#_9bff3da5-d8a6-4ff2-b526-bc8da8a248c7]
*To specify the recipients of the notification (in the '''To''' box), you can use the data fields (as the placeholders, separated with semicolons) that hold user identifiers and whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. For example, if you need to monitor cases and send notifications to assignees, you can use a placeholder for the identifier of the assignee, such as {{((CRCase_ownerID!PKID))}}. 
*You use the needed fields to specify which entity should be opened by the mobile app after a user taps the notification (in the '''Destination Entity ID''' box). Make sure that the {{NoteID}} data field is present in the results of the generic inquiry for the entity. For example, suppose that you selected ''Sales Orders'' in '''Destination Screen ID''' and want to open a particular order for the user; then you need to select the {{NoteID}} data field for the {{SOOrder}} object in '''Destination Entity ID'''.
*To specify the subject ('''Title''') of the notification template, you can use any data fields whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. For example, the subject could be {{Opportunity ((CROpportunity_opportunityID)) has been assigned to you}}. 
*In the body of the notification template (on the '''Message''' tab), you can click '''Insert Data Field''' on the formatting toolbar to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value is retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value was retrieved before the business event occurred. You can use this ability to demonstrate how the value of the data field has changed, for example, a case status has changed from ''New'' to ''Open''.

When the business event occurs and the system processes the subscriber of the ''Mobile Push Notification'' type, the system extracts the values of the fields specified for placeholders of the template (from the results of the generic inquiry that satisfy the conditions) and inserts these values into the notification. The system then sends the push notification or notifications to appropriate mobile devices of the recipients.{br}

If the notification has been sent successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the notification template, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.
==SMS Notifications==
If a subscriber to a business event is a mobile text notification, when the business event occurs, the system sends a mobile text notification (or multiple text notifications) to the mobile devices of particular recipients, based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event.{br}

The system uses an SMS service account configured on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_35|SMS Providers] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203535|SM203535]) form to send mobile text notifications. You can configure an account with the Amazon or Twilio service provider.{br}

You configure a subscriber of the ''Mobile SMS Notification'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204004|SM204004]) form. On this form, you must specify the SMS delivery method, the service provider, the description, the recipients of the notifications, and the template for the message. Also, in the '''Screen''' box, you specify the generic inquiry of the business event. ((({S:Warn}The easiest way to create a text notification for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Mobile SMS Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form with the ''SMS'' option selected in the '''Delivery Method''' box and the correct value selected in the '''Screen''' box.
)))
In the notification template you define on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form, you can use placeholders for the values of the form elements. As the placeholders, you can use the data fields available in the results of the generic inquiry of the business event as follows:[anchor|#_40b737ba-3e86-4836-ae58-8a13fd766d1f]
*To specify the recipients of the notification (in the '''To''' box), you use the data fields (as the placeholders, separated with semicolons) that hold user phone numbers and whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can specify phone numbers explicitly, separated with semicolons. 
*:For example, if you want to send a text about a shipment confirmation to a customer, you can use a placeholder for the identifier of the customer&rsquo;s phone number, such as {{((SOShipment_customerID!DefContactID!Phone1))}}.
*In the body of the notification template (on the '''Message''' tab), you can click '''Insert Data Field''' on the formatting toolbar to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value is retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value was retrieved before the business event occurred. 
*:For example, suppose that you would like to notify a customer that the status of the case has changed to another one. You insert the {{((CRCase_status))}} data field, which represents the placeholder of the case status and whose value will be retrieved when the business event occurs. To show the previous status of the case, you click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' and select the same data field; the system will insert the placeholder with the {{PREV}} function, which in our example is {{PREV((CRCase_status))}}. When the event occurs, the system retrieves the value that the field had before the event has occurred. 

When the business event occurs and the system processes the subscriber of the ''Mobile SMS Notification'' type, the system extracts the values of the fields specified for placeholders of the template (from the results of the generic inquiry that satisfy the conditions) and inserts these values into the notification. The system then sends the text notification or notifications to the mobile devices of the recipients.{br}

If the notification has been sent successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the notification template, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.
==Import Scenarios==
If a subscriber is an import scenario, when the business event occurs, the system executes on the target Acumatica ERP form the sequence of instructions defined by the import scenario that you have specified for the event. With the import scenario, you can perform any action defined on the target Acumatica ERP form, such as release of a document.{br}

You configure a subscriber of the ''Import Scenario'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_25|Import Scenarios] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206025|SM206025]) form. We recommend that you open this form to create the subscriber from the '''Subscribers''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: You click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Import Scenario''' on the table toolbar and specify the name of the scenario in the '''Create Import Scenario Subscriber''' dialog box, which opens. {br}

When you enter the name and click '''OK''' to close the dialog box, the system automatically creates on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_15|Data Providers] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206015|SM206015]) form a data provider of the ''Business Process Provider'' type for the import scenario (if the provider has not been created earlier for the generic inquiry of the business event). For this provider, the ''ScreenID'' parameter on the '''Parameters''' tab is set to the generic inquiry of the business event. The provider has two schema objects on the '''Schema''' tab: ''Results'' and ''PreviousResults''. Each object includes all fields of the results of the generic inquiry. The ''Results'' object returns the values of these fields when the business event occurs. The ''PreviousResults'' object returns the values of these fields before the business event has occurred. {br}

When the data provider has been created, the system opens the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_25|Import Scenarios] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206025|SM206025]) form with the import scenario name and the data provider specified. On the form, you complete creation of the import scenario by specifying the following:[anchor|#_817444ab-02a3-42b6-b456-a5fcd1dcaf9c]
*In the '''Screen Name''' box, the target Acumatica ERP form (which can be any Acumatica ERP form) on which the system should execute the sequence of instructions when the business event occurs.
*In the '''Provider Object''' box, the ''Results'' provider object or the ''PreviousResults'' provider object, depending on whether you want the system to extract the values before the business event has occurred or the values when the business event has occurred. The system uses the specified results of the generic inquiry to perform the sequence of instructions on the target form. 
*On the '''Mapping''' tab, the mapping of the import scenario—that is, the sequence of instructions that the system should perform on the target form when the business event occurs. When you are mapping fields, you should first map the key fields: the fields that the system uses to distinguish records that belong to different documents. After you have mapped the key fields, you should map other fields in the order in which you would fill them in on the form. At the end of the mapping of the scenario that creates or updates data in the system, to save the record to the database, you have to insert a row with the ''&lt;Action: Save&gt;'' action. For details about import scenario mapping, see [HelpRoot_Integration\IS__mng_Scenario_Mapping|Configuring Scenario Mapping].

You can also specify other parameters of the import scenario and source and target restrictions. For more information about import scenario configuration, see [HelpRoot_Integration\IS__mng_Configuring_Import_Scenarios|Configuring Import Scenarios].{br}

When the business event occurs and the system processes the ''Import Scenario'' subscriber, the system extracts the values (either the values before the business event has occurred or the values when the business event has occurred, depending on the provider object you specified for the import scenario) of the fields of the generic inquiry results and uses them as the source fields of the import scenario. The system executes on the target Acumatica ERP form the sequence of instructions defined by the import scenario. {br}

If the scenario has been executed successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the import scenario, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.
